## Phase 1: Data Collection Pipeline

**Where the code runs:** Google Colab (scheduled notebook) or a cheap CPU VM ($5/mo DigitalOcean/Railway)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Data collection does NOT need a GPU. A simple CPU instance or even a Colab notebook on a timer can scrape all 87 cameras every 60 seconds.

### What the collector does:
1. Hits `data.gov.sg/v1/transport/traffic-images` every 60 seconds
2. Downloads all 87 camera images
3. Simultaneously fetches: weather (temperature + forecast), taxi GPS count, PM2.5, flood alerts
4. Saves to structured folders: `data/raw/{YYYY-MM-DD}/{camera_id}/{HH-MM-SS}.jpg`
5. Writes `metadata.jsonl` per camera per day with all fields

### Metadata schema per frame:
```json
{
  "timestamp": "2026-03-08T15:00:00+08:00",
  "camera_id": "1701",
  "latitude": 1.323604,
  "longitude": 103.858780,
  "image_path": "data/raw/2026-03-08/1701/15-00-00.jpg",
  "image_hash_sha256": "abc123...",
  "image_width": 1920,
  "image_height": 1080,
  "weather_condition": "Partly Cloudy",
  "temperature_celsius": 31.2,
  "pm25_reading": 18,
  "taxi_count_nearby_5km": 42,
  "flood_active": false
}
```

### Collection duration targets:
| Duration | Images | Size (est.) | What It Enables |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 day | ~125K | ~2 GB | Proof of concept, test pipeline |
| 1 week | ~875K | ~14 GB | Time-of-day patterns, basic temporal analysis |
| 2 weeks | ~1.75M | ~28 GB | Weather variation, weekday vs weekend patterns |
| 1 month | ~3.75M | ~60 GB | Full Kaggle-publishable dataset, seasonal patterns |

### Error handling:
- Camera offline → log it, skip, continue (some cameras go stale for hours)
- API timeout → retry 3x with exponential backoff
- Duplicate frames → detect via image hash, flag but still save (useful metadata)

