## Phase 2: Dataset Formatting for Kaggle

### Kaggle dataset structure:
```
singapore-smart-city-traffic/
├── images/
│   ├── train/          # 70% — stratified by camera, time, weather
│   ├── val/            # 15%
│   └── test/           # 15%
├── metadata/
│   ├── frames.csv      # One row per image with all metadata columns
│   ├── frames.parquet  # Same data, efficient format
│   ├── cameras.csv     # Camera ID → GPS, resolution, expressway name
│   └── statistics.json # Dataset-level stats
├── annotations/        # YOLO format (if auto-labeled)
│   ├── train/
│   ├── val/
│   └── test/
├── DATASET_CARD.md
├── LICENSE             # ODbL (matching data.gov.sg terms)
└── citation.bib
```

### Auto-labeling pipeline (runs on Colab GPU):
1. Run fine-tuned YOLOv11 on all collected frames
2. Save detections as YOLO-format `.txt` annotation files
3. Include confidence scores in metadata (for filtering and failure analysis)
4. **This is the unique part** — most Kaggle datasets are either raw images or manually labeled. Yours is auto-labeled with a domain-specific model + confidence metadata.

### Stratified splits:
- By camera location (ensure all cameras represented in train/val/test)
- By time bucket (dawn 5-7, morning 7-10, midday 10-15, evening 15-19, night 19-5)
- By weather condition

### Deduplication:
- Use perceptual hashing (pHash) to detect near-identical frames
- Static cameras often return identical images at night — deduplicate but log frequency

