## Phase 3: Failure Analytics

### Failure taxonomy (6 categories):

| Category | Detection Method | What It Catches |
|---|---|---|
| `LOW_CONFIDENCE` | Mean detection confidence < 0.25 | Model struggling on this frame |
| `WEATHER_DEGRADED` | Confidence drops when weather = rain/fog | Weather-specific model weakness |
| `LOW_RESOLUTION` | Camera resolution = 320×240 | ~12 cameras have tiny images |
| `OCCLUSION` | IoU between boxes > 0.7 | Overlapping vehicles, model confused |
| `NIGHT_MODE` | Mean pixel intensity < 60 | Dark frame, poor visibility |
| `CAMERA_FAILURE` | Hash matches previous N frames OR blank image | Dead/frozen camera feed |

### Per-camera reliability scorecard:
```
Camera 1701 (CTE/Braddell):  Overall: 94.2%
  ├── Clear:    98.1%  ├── Rain:     82.3%  (↓ 15.8%)
  ├── Night:    71.5%  (↓ 26.6%)  ├── Fog:      65.0%  (↓ 33.1%)
  └── Worst failure mode: NIGHT_MODE (28.5% of night frames)
```

### Failure report outputs:
- `failure_report.json` — machine-readable, per-camera, per-condition stats
- `failure_report.md` — human-readable with charts
- Per-camera reliability heatmap (camera × condition → success rate)
- Confidence distribution plots grouped by weather
- "Top 10 worst cameras" ranking with root cause

**The story this tells:**
> *"Camera 1001 (320×240, ECP) has 35% failure rate in rain due to low resolution + water droplets. Recommendation: either exclude from rain-condition analytics or apply super-resolution preprocessing."*

This is what makes a senior engineer say "this person thinks about production systems."

